Vicki Momberg's bid to appeal her two-year sentence in connection with a racism-related conviction has been postponed. The postponement, in the Gauteng High Court in Johannesburg on Monday, was brought about by Momberg's change of legal representation. On November 3, 2017, Momberg was found guilty of four counts of crimen injuria after she called a black officer the k-word 48 times when he came to her aid following a smash-and-grab incident. In March 2018, she was sentenced to two years in jail with an additional one year suspended. This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. WATCH: Vicki Momberg sentenced to 2 years in prison for using the k-word Former real estate agent Vicki Momberg was sentenced to an effective two years in prison by the Randburg Magistrate's Court on Wednesday for her racist tirade in 2016. The court sentenced her to three years, with one year suspended. The former real estate agent was granted R2 000 bail in the Randburg Magistrate's Court in August last year, pending the outcome of an appeal against her conviction and sentence, News24 reported earlier. ALSO READ: Vicki Momberg granted bail, pending her appeal The matter is expected to resume on June 11, 2019. KEEP UPDATED on the latest news by subscribing to our FREE newsletter. - FOLLOW News24 on Twitter 